th of Radom, had in 1931 a population of nearly 30,000, of whom more than a third were Jews. The persistence of traditional ways of life and the importance of the local hasidic rebbe, Yechiel-Meier (Halevi) Halsztok, as well as the introduction of such modernities as bubble gum, are clearly and effectively described here. This memoir is remarkable for the ability of its author to recall so many events in detail and for the way he is able to be fair to all those caught up in the tragic dilemmas of those years. It is a major contribution to our understanding of the fate of Jews in smaller Polish towns during the Second World War and the conditions which made it possible for some of them, like Rubin, to survive.  afunded by National Endowment for the Humanities and The Andrew W. Mellon Foundation Humanities Open Book Program  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zPolandvPersonal narratives. 0aJewish children in the HolocaustzPolandzOstrowiec ŚwiętokrzyskivBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh1 aPolonsky, Antony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb2 aNational Endowment for the Humanities and The Andrew W. Mellon Foundation Humanities Open Book Programefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015z978311068814608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertReligious Studies ASPz978311071683240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781618116840?locatt=mode:legacyzO